### Research on Use Cases and User Stories

# Use Cases
3. Chloe --> [UML use case diagrams](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4emxjxonNRI)
* **System**: whatever you're developing (e.g. website, software component, business process, app, etc)
  * Represented by a rectangle (defines the scope of the system), with the name of the system at the top (e.g. 'Banking App')
* **Actor**: someone or something that uses our system to achieve a goal (e.g. person, organization, another system, external device)
  * Can be represented as a stick figure
  * Must be placed outside the system â†’ actors are external objects
  * Must be thought of as types or categories (e.g. 'customer & bank' NOT 'John & Chase Bank')
  * **Primary Actors**: initiates the use of the system (e.g. customer interacts with banking app)
    * Must be placed to the left of the system
  * **Secondary Actors**: reactionary (e.g. bank only acts when the customer activates banking app)
    * Must be placed to the right of the system
* **Use Case**: represents an action that accomplishes some sort of task within the system (e.g. 'Log in', 'Check balance', 'Transfer funds', 'Make payment')
  * Represented by an oval shape within the system
  * Put use cases in a logical order if possible (e.g. 'Log in' at the top of the use cases because it is the first thing a customer does when using the app)
* **Association Relationship**: signifies a basic communication or interaction
  * Represented by a solid line between an actor and a use case (e.g. line between Customer and 'Check Balance,' between 'Check Balance' and Bank)
* **Include Relationship**: shows dependencies between a Base Use Case and an Included Use Case (e.g. Base Use Case: 'Log in', Included Use Case: 'Verify password')
  * Everytime the Base Use Case is executed, Included Use Case is executed as well; Base Use Case requires Included Use Case in order to be complete
  * Represented by a dashed arrow from Base Use Case to Included Use Case, with `<<include>>` in the middle of the arrow
* **Extend Relationship**: shows dependencies between a Base Use Case and an Extend Use Case (e.g. Base Use Case: 'Log in', Extend Use Case: 'Display login error')
  * When the Base Use Case is executed, the Extend Use Case will happen sometimes but not all the times (only when certain criteria is met)
  * Represented by a dashed arrow from Extend Use Case to Base Use Case, with `<<extend>>` in the middle of the arrow
* **Generalization Relationship** (aka Inheritance): shows dependencies between a General Use Case (parent) and Specialized Use Cases (children) (e.g. General Use Case: 'Make Payment', Specialized Use Cases: 'Pay from checking', 'Pay from savings')
  * Represented by a square shaped arrow from the Specialized Use Cases to the General Use Case
  * Can have Generalization relationships between actors (e.g. General Actor: customer, Specialized Actors: new customer, returning customer)
* **Extension Point**: detailed versions of extend relationships within use cases
  * Represented by a horizontal line splitting the oval use case, with Extension Points listed below the line (within the oval)

# User Story
3. Chloe --> [AgileModeling-Stories.pdf](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1FKmhX_KOO2gUZ596GXS2Z2xAmurR3E7p/view)
* **user story**: a high level definition of a requirement, containing just enough information so that developers can produce a reasonable estimate of the effort to implement it
* **example informal user stories**: "Students can purchase monthly parking passes online," "Parking passes can be paid via credit cards"
* **important considerations for writing informal user stories**:
  * Stakeholders write user stories (not the developers)
  * Use the simplest tool (index cards)
  * Remember non-functional requirements (stay away from technical requirements)
  * Indicate the estimated size (time to complete)
  * Indicate the priority (keep it simple)
  * Optionally include a unique identifier
* **formal user story suggested format**: As a (role) I want (something) so that (benefit).
  * example: "As a Student I want to purchase a parking pass so that I can drive to school"
* **agile change management process**: work items, including stories, are addressed in priority order
  * each iteration implement the highest priority work items
  * each new work item is prioritized and added to the stack
  * work items may be reprioritized or removed at any time
* **user stories throughout the agile life cycle**:
  * **Iteration 0**: create a stack of user stories as part of requirements envisioning
  * **Construction**: identify new stories, split existing stories that are too large to be implemented in a single iteration, reprioritize/remove stories
  * **Release**: harden the system; sometimes new stories will be identified during this phase but it is not the common focus, place on the stack in priority order as normal
* **user stories contain little information, flesh them out in times like**:
  * During JIT analysis/model storming with stakeholders
  * During iteration planning
  * During implementation
* **Epics**: large user stories, typically ones that are too big to implement in a single iteration (need to be disaggregated into smaller user stories)
* **Themes**: collection of related user stories used to organize stories into releases or to organize them so that subteams can work on them
  * e.g. a university registration system might have themes around students, course management, transcript generation, etc
